<Prose
  title="How to Study This Course"
  description="How the free geomancy course works: pacing, the casting journal, self-grading against model answers, and the citation discipline of the exercises."
  crumbs={[{ name: 'The Course', href: '/course/' }, { name: 'How to Study' }]}
  kicker="The Geomancy Course"
>
  <p>
    This course is free, and it asks nothing of you but time and seriousness. Everything you need
    is on this site: the lessons, the primary texts they assign, and full model answers to every
    exercise. What no website can supply is the discipline of a correspondence course, so you
    must supply it yourself. This page explains how.
  </p>

  <h2>The open approach</h2>
  <p>
    Geomancy comes to us from a world with a different picture of the cosmos: one in which the
    heavens act on the earth, and the hand of a person earnestly seeking an answer is moved to
    set down points that are not accidents. You do not need to believe this to study geomancy. You
    do need to <em>suspend disbelief</em>: to work inside the older worldview rather than translating it on the fly into psychology or coincidence. Judge the system
    from inside, on its own terms. What you make of it afterwards is your own
    affair.
  </p>

  <h2>Pacing and mastery</h2>
  <p>
    The lessons are sequential. Each assumes complete command of everything before it, and the
    later lessons are unreadable without the earlier ones, not as a policy, but as a fact about
    the material. There is no calendar, no cohort and no deadline; speed is irrelevant and nobody
    is counting. Expect two to three weeks of unhurried work per lesson: the assigned reading
    first, then the lesson itself, then the exercises.
  </p>
  <p>
    Every lesson ends with a mastery checklist: “you are ready to continue when you can…”. Treat
    it as a gate, not a suggestion. If an item fails, the place to fix it is in that lesson, not
    three lessons later when the gap has compounded.
  </p>

  <h2>Do the exercises before opening the answers</h2>
  <p>
    Each exercise is followed by a model answer or a fully worked solution, folded shut. The
    entire value of the course lives in the gap between attempting an exercise and reading its
    answer. An answer read before the attempt teaches almost nothing; the same answer read after
    a real attempt (especially a failed one) teaches permanently. Write your answers down, in
    full sentences, before you look. For the drills, show your working; for the quizzes, write
    each answer down before revealing the key, as if a demanding instructor were going to read
    the result, because the only instructor you have is you.
  </p>

  <h2>The citation discipline</h2>
  <p>
    The exercises require you to cite the sources wherever they ask for one: author, title, and
    locator, in the form used throughout this site. This is not academic ceremony. It trains the single most important
    habit in source-based practice: distinguishing what the sources actually say from what you
    assume it says. If you can't point to the passage, you don't know it; you remember
    something like it. Quotations from Cattan, Heydon, the pseudo-Agrippa and Gerard of Cremona
    carry source weight in this course; Crowley's handbook is admitted as a modern comparison, and is
    flagged as such wherever it is assigned.
  </p>

  <h2>The casting journal</h2>
  <p>
    From Lesson 4 onward you will cast real charts for real questions, and you must keep a
    journal of them: the question and the moment it was asked, the full chart, your reading
    written <em>before</em> the outcome is known, and later the outcome itself, with notes on
    what you misread. A geomancer's skill is built almost entirely out of this record. A paper
    notebook follows older practice and has the advantage that you cannot quietly revise it.
  </p>

  <h2>What you will need</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Pen and paper: geomancy was practiced for a thousand years with nothing else.</li>
    <li>A notebook for the casting journal.</li>
    <li>
      The texts, all free on this site: start from <a href={withBase('/library/')}>the library</a>. Nothing
      is for sale here and nothing ever will be.
    </li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    The site's reference sections (<a href={withBase('/figures/')}>the figures</a>,
    <a href={withBase('/houses/')}>the houses</a>, <a href={withBase('/techniques/')}>the techniques</a>) remain open
    beside the course at all times; the lessons link into them constantly. When you are ready,
    begin with <a href={withBase('/course/')}>Lesson 1</a>.
  </p>
</Prose>
